      "definition": "The Whiskey Rebellion of 1794, which broke out when backcountry Pennsylvania farmers sought to block collection of the new tax on distilled spirits, reinforced this conviction. \"Political freedom\" included the right to \"exercise watchfulness and inspection, upon the conduct of public officers.\" Blamed by Federalists for helping to inspire the Whiskey Rebellion, the societies disappeared by the end of 1795. But the rise of political parties seeking to mobilize voters in hotly contested elections, the emergence of the \"self-created societies,\" the stirrings of women's political consciousness, and even armed uprisings like the Whiskey Rebellion broadened and deepened the democratization of public life set in motion by the American Revolution.",
