      "chapterId": "chapter8",
      "type": "Term",
      "front": "An Expanding Public Sphere",
      "back": "When he left office, a Republican newspaper declared that his name had become synonymous with \"political iniquity\" and \"legalized corruption.\" The debates of the 1790s produced not only one of the most intense periods of partisan warfare in American history but also an enduring expansion of the public sphere, and with it the democratic content of American freedom. \"She is alive and active,\" the British novelist Virginia Woolf wrote in the 1920s, \"she argues and experiments, we hear her voice and trace her influence even now among the living.\" The expansion of the public sphere offered new opportunities to women. When Jefferson became president, on the other hand, he sought to quarantine and destroy the hemisphere's second independent republic.",
