      "type": "Term",
      "front": "The Rights of Women",
      "back": "The treaty that transferred Louisiana to the United States promised that all free inhabitants would enjoy \"the rights, advantages, and immunities of citizens.\" Spanish and French civil codes, unlike British and American law, recognized women as co-owners of family property. French and Spanish law accorded free blacks, many of whom were the offspring of unions between white military officers and slave women, nearly all the rights of white citizens. But like the activities of the Democratic-Republican societies, the discussion of women's status helped to popularize the language of rights in the new republic.",
